chester, Dorset, England":"Dorchester, Dorset, England","Fordington Saint George, Dorsetshire, Engalnd":"Fordington, Dorset, England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"Abt 1560–December 1625":"circa 1560–december 1625","1580–Female":"1580–Overleden","1604–1665":"1604–1665","1560–1625":"1560–1625","Abt 1560":"circa 1560","1665":"1665","1560":"1560","1580":"1580","1604":"1604","December 1625":"december 1625","1625":"1625","Dorchester, Dorset, England":"Dorchester, Dorset, England","Fordington Saint George, Dorsetshire, Engalnd":"Fordington, Dorset, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"Abt 1560–December 1625":"about 1560–December 1625","1580–Female":"1580–Deceased","1604–1665":"1604–1665","1560–1625":"1560–1625","Abt 1560":"about 1560","1665":"1665","1560":"1560","1580":"1580","1604":"1604","December 1625":"December 1625","1625":"1625","Dorchester, Dorset, England":"Dorchester, Dorset, England","Fordington Saint George, Dorsetshire, Engalnd":"Fordington, Dorset, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Seager","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: from the Middle English personal name <i>Segar</i>, <i>Segor</i>, <i>Sagar</i> (Old English <i>Sǣgār</i>, from <i>sǣ</i> ‘sea’ + <i>gār</i> ‘spear’). Variants of its medieval forms may sometimes have been identical with those of <b>Sigger</b> (see   Seago  ), leading to confusion of the two names.","Americanized form of German   Seeger  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Seegars","meanings":["Variant of   Seager   or   Seegers  ."]},{"name":"Seago","meanings":["English (Norfolk):","variant of   Seager   with an altered pronunciation of the final syllable.","variant of <b>Sigger</b>, from the Middle English personal names <i>Sigar</i>, <i>Siger</i>, and <i>Sigher</i>, from either Old English <i>Sigegār</i>, ancient Germanic <i>Sigger</i>, or Old Norse <i>Sigarr</i>, Old Danish and Swedish <i>Sighar</i>. In each case the name arises from roots meaning ‘victory’ + ‘spear’. In medieval Norfolk the source of the name was probably mostly Scandinavian. Middle English <i>Seger</i>, <i>Segor</i> may have been variants, leading to confusion with   Seager  ."]},{"name":"Segar","meanings":["English: variant of   Seager  .","English: variant of   Sager  .","Americanized form of Dutch   Seger   1."]},{"name":"Segars","meanings":["Variant of   Seager   or, possibly,   Seegers  ."]},{"name":"Siggers","meanings":["English (Essex and London): patronymic, with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>, from the Middle English personal names <i>Sigar</i>, <i>Siger</i>, and <i>Sigher</i>, either from Old English <i>Sigegār</i>, ancient Germanic <i>Sigger</i>, or Old Norse <i>Sigarr</i>, Old Danish and Swedish <i>Sighar</i>, in each case from roots meaning ‘victory’ + ‘spear’. Middle English <i>Seger</i>, <i>Segor</i> may have been variants, leading to confusion with   Seager  , from Old English <i>Sǣgār</i>, in which the first element is <i>sǣ</i> ‘sea’. Compare   Seago  ."]}]},{"name":"Richard","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Rikert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]},{"name":"Rickert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Richard Seager was born about 1560, in Fordington, Dorset, England, United Kingdom. He had at least 1 daughter with Mrs Richard Seager. He died in December 1625, at the age of 66."},"et":{"Abt 1560–December 1625":"umbes 1560–detsember 1625","1580–Female":"1580–Surnud","1604–1665":"1604–1665","1560–1625":"1560–1625","Abt 1560":"umbes 1560","1665":"1665","1560":"1560","1580":"1580","1604":"1604","December 1625":"detsember 1625","1625":"1625","Dorchester, Dorset, England":"Dorchester, Dorset, England","Fordington Saint George, Dorsetshire, Engalnd":"Fordington, Dorset, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"Abt 1560–December 1625":"noin 1560–joulukuu 1625","1580–Female":"1580–Kuollut","1604–1665":"1604–1665","1560–1625":"1560–1625","Abt 1560":"noin 1560","1665":"1665","1560":"1560","1580":"1580","1604":"1604","December 1625":"joulukuu 1625","1625":"1625","Dorchester, Dorset, England":"Dorchester, Dorset, England","Fordington Saint George, Dorsetshire, Engalnd":"Fordington, Dorset, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"Abt 1560–December 1625":"environ 1560–décembre 1625","1580–Female":"1580–Décédée","1604–1665":"1604–1665","1560–1625":"1560–1625","Abt 1560":"environ 1560","1665":"1665","1560":"1560","1580":"1580","1604":"1604","December 1625":"décembre 1625","1625":"1625","Dorchester, Dorset, England":"Dorchester, Dorset, Angleterre","Fordington Saint George, Dorsetshire, Engalnd":"Fordington, Dorset, Anglete